The file exports a function that takes two parameters, `type` and an object of settings (`data`). The type is expected to be one from the predefined list in this case `'community'`, but you could extend it with more types. 

In our example we have only default values for some properties which are specific per community-type.

If your use-case requires different logic based on certain conditions or dynamic configuration then consider using if-else statements inside export's return statement instead direct returning objects as I did here.
```javascript 
exportdefault (typeName,data)=>{

    let result={};

	if(typeName==='myCustomTypeName'){
      // configure according custom typeName   
     } else {  
      	result= {...defaults...}
   }

return(result);
}'; ```
This way exporting functions can handle complex configurations dynamically whereas simple constant defaults like above might not need such approach.`

